Hello East Dubuque Families,

We were informed by one of our families today that an organization called Kids First Community has been reaching out to our East Dubuque businesses soliciting donations on behalf of the ED School District. The district cut ties with this organization nearly two years ago. Please do not give any money to this company on behalf of the district. This company is in no way affiliated with the East Dubuque School District. Please pass this information on to all ED businesses.

post_text:
Hi, my name is Elizabeth Sand and I am the new Special Education teacher at East Dubuque Elementary. This is my first official year as a certified teacher, although you might have seen me around, as I was a paraprofessional here at East Dubuque the last couple of years while finishing school.
My husband and I are both East Dubuque natives and are raising our two children here. Our daughter Mia just started her Freshman year of high school and our son Theo just turned two in July! We also have an almost three year old puppy named Maddon. I love spending time with my family and friends, watching Mia play sports, going for walks, online shopping, watching the Cubs, and last but certainly not least, teaching!
I feel genuinely blessed that I am beginning my teaching career at the very school that I went to as a child. I also love the fact that my own children have and will attend here, as well as my niece, nephews, and my friend’s children. Community is very important to me and I am so happy and proud to be part of the Warrior family!!

post_text:
Our next installment of getting to know our new teachers comes from Mr. Harbaugh. He is the mentor for our new science teacher at the High School, Macayla Willis. Here is a note from Mr. Harbaugh:
Macayla has proven to be a very talented individual. Her background in computers/technology have proven very beneficial in this very unique and interesting school year. She has shown herself to be a very capable young teacher who I feel will be a great asset to not only the science department, but East Dubuque High School as well. On the downside, Macayla has made me realize just how long I have been at East Dubuque because her high school science teacher was a former student of mine.
Mr. Harbaugh

post_text: Hello I am Riley Asche. I grew up in Pearl City, IL and went to school there my whole life. I played football in high school as well as being in other various clubs. I then went to college at Northern Illinois University for my Physical Education Degree. I got my first job back home in Pearl City as the elementary PE teacher. I have done that for the last three years. I have also coached football, basketball, and track. My parents both coached while I was growing up so I fell in love with being in a school setting. I have one younger brother who is currently at Illinois St. on a football scholarship. My greatest memories at Pearl City over the last few years are the end of the year Field Days that I organize for the entire elementary. As well as going to the class 2A semifinals in football in 2018 as the defensive coordinator. I look forward to a great year at East Dubuque!

Due to the East Dubuque School District having positive cases of COVID four of the last five days and a number of students and staff having to quarantine, we will move to Remote Learning for all students until Monday, September 14. At that time we will return to In-Person learning for all students that have not opted in full remote learning.

Tomorrow, Wednesday, Sept. 2 will be a Remote Learning Day for all students at the Junior High and High School. It will be a Remote Planning Day for Elementary Students. The Elementary Students will start Remote Learning on Thursday, Sept. 3.

Parents, please see the email that was sent from the district for details.

post_text:
East Dubuque Graduation

Reminder that the Graduation Ceremony for the 2020 Class will be on Sunday, July 19 at 6:30 at the football stadium. If you do plan on attending please come and be seated by 6:15 at the latest. At 6:15 the graduates and their parents will parade in (in their vehicles) and then be seated. We ask that no one sets chairs on the walking track due to this procession. You are welcome to sit on the hill or in the bleachers. Please social distance and wear a mask. Thank you for staying safe.

We plan for the ceremony to be over by 7:30 with the graduates and their parents again processing out of the stadium. We ask that all remain until the graduates process out. Thank you.

Congratulations to our class of 2020. You are all so very worth the wait of this ceremony!

If there is inclement weather on Sunday we will make an announcement by 5:00 of alternate plans for the Ceremony.

post_text:
Alex
Alex Anger has been involved in football, basketball, and track and field throughout his
four years. Alex has enjoyed friendships that have formed over the years. He was
looking forward to another track season. His ultimate goals were to beat his uncle’s
record in the discus (which has been held since 1987) and make a repeat appearance
at state. Alex will be pursuing an associates degree in powersports technician at
Minnesota State Community and Technical College in Detroit Lakes, Minnesota.

post_text:
Yearbook News! We need your help.

East Dubuque Schools will have three yearbooks.

High School grades 9-12, Ms. Hammons khammons@edbqhs.org

Junior High grades 7-8, Ms. Stierman kstierman@edbqhs.org

Elementary grades preschool-6th, Ms. Stierman kstierman@edbqhs.org

We need your help.

1. eLearning—assignments, workspaces, students working on projects

2. Nontraditional learning—cooking, cleaning up the community, gardening, cards/notes, etc.

3. Family projects—art projects—hearts in the window, rock painting, walking/hiking, playing board games, putting together puzzles, etc.

4. Seniors—decorating your front door with jerseys or graduation

5. Junior High—extra curricular activities, volleyball, football, basketball, quiz bowl, student council. Pictures from the ski trip, homecoming parade, candid shots at school or at activities.

We need you to capture some photos for us. We want to include this time in the yearbook. We are living history--imagine looking back at this 5, 10 or 20 years from now.

Thank you for your help,

text:
Yearbook News! We need your help.

East Dubuque Schools will have three yearbooks.

High School grades 9-12, Ms. Hammons khammons@edbqhs.org

Junior High grades 7-8, Ms. Stierman kstierman@edbqhs.org

Elementary grades preschool-6th, Ms. Stierman kstierman@edbqhs.org

We need your help.

1. eLearning—assignments, workspaces, students working on projects

2. Nontraditional learning—cooking, cleaning up the community, gardening, cards/notes, etc.

3. Family projects—art projects—hearts in the window, rock painting, walking/hiking, playing board games, putting together puzzles, etc.

4. Seniors—decorating your front door with jerseys or graduation

5. Junior High—extra curricular activities, volleyball, football, basketball, quiz bowl, student council. Pictures from the ski trip, homecoming parade, candid shots at school or at activities.

We need you to capture some photos for us. We want to include this time in the yearbook. We are living history--imagine looking back at this 5, 10 or 20 years from now.

Thank you for your help,

Kathy Stierman and Kelsey Hammons

PLEASE VOTE!

Next Tuesday is an important day for a lot of reasons and we hope you can all get out and vote. While public gatherings are not encouraged at this time due to illnesses, you are still encouraged to participate in the voting process. Please see the note from the Governor's office:

ELECTIONS

• The election will proceed as scheduled on Tuesday, March 17. This is a fundamental function of government, and the state is committed to making sure the election proceeds with as little disruption as possible.
• Local jurisdictions are encouraged to expand hours for early voting over the weekend to reduce the number of people who would need to vote on Election Day.
• Voters who have not already submitted a vote by mail application can pick up a vote by mail ballot through Monday at their local election offices.

We have contacted the Court House and will notify you of any changes in voting hours over the weekend.

Did you know?
If the East Dubuque School District were going to update its facilities just for space needs based on national averages we would need to do a $3.9 Million dollar project at the Elementary School and a $2.4 Million dollar project at the Junior High/High School. Again, that would be to just bring us up to national averages.

If we were going to build a new Elementary School on the existing site the cost would be $16.9 Million.

These figures are according to the architects at FEH Design.

post_text: Want to know what to do over the break? If you love board games and love Math then the AP Calculus students have just the thing for you. About a month ago I asked the students to create a board game using all of the derivative rules we learned in AP Calculus. They formed two groups and created Calculus Boat Destruction (Battleship) and Derivative Dilemma (Trouble). The students made these board games and incorporated derivative rules such as power, chain, product, quotient, trig, inverse trig, exponential/logarithmic rules. They spent numerous hours constructing the game and got to relive their younger days by playing these classic games while also practicing important Calculus concepts.

post_text: Come to our district Open House to learn more about our Schools and our Facilites on Thursday evening, November 21st from 6:00 pm to 8:00 pm at the Elementary School. If you can't make it Thursday, please come the Junior High/High School building on Saturday, Nov. 23rd from 9:00 am to 12:00 noon. We will have stations set up for your information and to answer any questions that you may have about education, facilities, finances, or to give you a tour. We hope to see you there.

post_text: East Dubuque Kindergarten students go to College! Our Kindergarten students were able to spend a day on the campus at the University of Dubuque and catch a show at the Heritage Center, eat lunch at the cafe, and meet a local author. It was quite the day for some of our youngest students who now have going to college planted in their brains! Thanks for a great day U of D! We have a wonderful partnership rolling along and it is EXCELLENT!

JOIN US as our WARRIOR Family surrounds and support Deb Theill, Carla Kipper and Gabe Hilby at our TEAMING UP FOR A CURE event THURSDAY, OCTOBER 10th as we team up with the GALENA PIRATES to raise money for these three Warriors currently fighting cancer!



VOLLEYBALL GAME TIMES:

FRESHMAN 5pm

JV 6 pm

VARSITY 7 pm



The Community has been so generous! We have over 75 silent auction items/baskets donated! Bring your checkbook and buy 50/50 tickets, a cancer ribbon cookie, and bid on our wide array of Silent Auction items! Thanks in advance for your support!! Come cheer on your WARRIOR Volleyball players!!!

post_text: The elementary school has been saving pop tops for the Ronald McDonald House in Iowa City. We were able to deliver 3 huge bags to help support families in need. 💙 Last year they raised over $14,000 from pop tops. When we all do a little something, great things happen! ❤
